              { year: 2024, marks: 3, q: "What is meant by 'Legal Personality'? How is a corporation treated as a legal person?", a: "Legal Personality refers to the capacity of an entity to possess rights, bear duties, and be subject to legal obligations recognised by law. An entity with legal personality can sue and be sued, own property, and enter into contracts.\n\nNatural persons (human beings) automatically have legal personality. But law also recognises 'legal persons' — entities other than humans that are given a legal identity.\n\nCorporation as legal person (separate legal entity):\nThe landmark case Salomon v Salomon & Co. Ltd (1897) established that a company is a legal person separate and distinct from its shareholders. The company can:\n- Own property in its own name\n- Enter into contracts independently\n- Sue and be sued in court\n- Continue to exist even after all original members have died or left\n\nConsequence: The shareholders have limited liability — they are not personally responsible for the company's debts beyond what they invested. This is the cornerstone of modern company law." },
              { year: 2023, marks: 2, q: "How are religious deities treated as legal persons in Indian law?", a: "In Indian law, a Hindu deity (idol) installed in a temple is recognised as a 'juristic person' — a legal entity with the ability to hold property and to sue or be sued through a manager (shebait/manager of the temple).\n\nKey case: The Privy Council in Pramatha Nath Mullick v. Pradyumna Kumar Mullick (1925) established that an idol of a deity is a 'juristic entity' in India — it can own the temple property, sue for its rights, and have decisions made on its behalf by the shebait (trustee).\n\nSignificance: Temple properties are owned by the deity (through the temple trust), not by individual priests or temple committees. This protects temple property from individual misappropriation." }
