                { year: 2023, marks: 3, q: "Distinguish between 'Stock' and 'Flow' concepts with two examples of each.", a: "Stock: A quantity measured at a particular point in time. It has no time dimension — it is simply how much exists at this moment.\nExamples: Wealth of a person (₹10 lakh on 1 January 2024), water in a tank at 9 AM, total money supply on a given date.\n\nFlow: A quantity measured over a period of time. It has a time dimension — it can only be measured over a specified interval (per week, per month, per year).\nExamples: National income (₹200 lakh crore per year), salary (₹50,000 per month), investment (₹10 crore in a quarter).\n\nRelationship: A flow adds to or subtracts from a stock. Income (flow) adds to wealth (stock); depreciation (flow) reduces the capital stock." },
                { year: 2022, marks: 3, q: "Explain the circular flow of income in a two-sector economy.", a: "The circular flow of income in a two-sector economy (households and firms) shows how income and expenditure flow continuously between the two sectors:\n\n1. Households own all factors of production (land, labour, capital, enterprise).\n2. They supply these factors to firms in the factor market.\n3. Firms pay factor payments — rent, wages, interest, profit — to households. This constitutes households' income.\n4. Households spend their income purchasing goods and services from firms in the product market.\n5. This expenditure becomes revenue for firms, enabling them to pay factor incomes again.\n\nThus, income flows from firms to households (as factor payments) and returns from households to firms (as consumption expenditure) — creating a continuous circular flow.\n\nKey insight: Total output = Total income = Total expenditure in a closed economy without saving or government." }
