                { year: 2024, marks: 4, q: "Describe the structure and functions of the UN Security Council. What is meant by the 'veto power'?", a: "The UN Security Council (UNSC) is the most powerful organ of the United Nations, responsible for maintaining international peace and security.\n\nStructure:\n- 15 members: 5 permanent (P5: USA, Russia, China, UK, France) and 10 non-permanent elected for 2-year terms by the General Assembly.\n- Decisions on substantive matters require 9 affirmative votes including all P5 members.\n\nFunctions:\n1. Authorise UN peacekeeping operations\n2. Impose sanctions on states threatening peace\n3. Authorise use of military force ('Chapter VII' resolutions)\n4. Recommend admission of new UN members\n5. Recommend appointment of Secretary-General\n\nVeto power: Each P5 member can block any substantive UNSC resolution by voting against it — this is the veto. Even if 14 of 15 members approve a resolution, a single P5 'no' vote defeats it.\n\nCriticism: The veto makes the UNSC ineffective when the interests of major powers are at stake — during the Cold War and in recent conflicts (Syria, Russia-Ukraine), vetoes prevented action." },
                { year: 2023, marks: 3, q: "What is India's case for a permanent seat on the UN Security Council?", a: "India has been campaigning for a permanent seat on the UN Security Council as part of the demand for UNSC reform. India's arguments:\n\n1. Demographic weight: India is the world's most populous country with over 1.4 billion people. Decisions of global significance should reflect the world's population, not just great powers of 1945.\n2. Economic size: India is one of the world's top-5 largest economies and a growing global economic power.\n3. UN contribution: India is one of the largest contributors to UN peacekeeping missions, having sent over 180,000 troops across dozens of missions — more than any P5 member.\n4. Regional leadership: India is the dominant power in South Asia and plays an important role in Asian and global affairs.\n5. Democratic credentials: India is the world's largest democracy, making it a model for democratic governance in the developing world.\n\nChallenge: UNSC reform requires agreement among P5 members, who are reluctant to dilute their power by adding new permanent members." }
