                { year: 2024, marks: 4, q: "Why was Congress the dominant party in India's early elections? What were the factors behind its dominance?", a: "Congress dominated Indian politics from 1952 to 1967, winning the first three general elections with large majorities. Several factors explain this dominance:\n\n1. Legacy of freedom struggle: Congress was identified with the independence movement. Most Indians saw it as 'the party that won us freedom' — this gave it enormous emotional and political capital that other parties could not match.\n\n2. Leadership quality: Congress had outstanding national leaders — Jawaharlal Nehru, Sardar Patel, Maulana Azad — whose national stature dwarfed all opposition leaders.\n\n3. Organisational reach: Congress had a well-organised party structure down to the village level, built over decades of mass mobilisation during the independence movement.\n\n4. Umbrella party character: Congress was not a narrowly ideological party — it accommodated conservatives, socialists, secularists, and regionalists. This ideological flexibility allowed it to absorb diverse social groups.\n\n5. Support of minorities: Congress's secular credentials attracted Muslim, Dalit, and other minority votes." },
                { year: 2023, marks: 3, q: "What were the main opposition parties in India during the 1950s-60s? What were their ideological orientations?", a: "In the 1950s and 1960s, the main opposition parties and their ideologies were:\n\n1. Communist Party of India (CPI): Marxist-Leninist ideology, supported Soviet Union, advocated land reform and workers' rights. Had support in Kerala, West Bengal, and Andhra Pradesh. Won government in Kerala in 1957 — the first democratically elected communist government in the world.\n\n2. Socialist Party (Praja Socialist Party, later): Centre-left, non-communist socialism. Led by figures like Ram Manohar Lohia and Jayaprakash Narayan. Strong on democratic socialism but lacked cohesive organisation.\n\n3. Bharatiya Jana Sangh (BJS): Right-of-centre Hindu nationalist party, founded by Shyama Prasad Mukherjee in 1951. Advocated Hindu cultural nationalism, opposition to Pakistan, and scrapping of Article 370. Forerunner of the BJP.\n\n4. Swatantra Party: Classical liberal/conservative party founded 1959, opposed to state controls and planning. Had support from former princes and industrialists. Advocated free market economics and limited government." }
