                { year: 2023, marks: 4, q: "What were the main challenges to the Congress system that emerged after the 1967 elections?", a: "The 1967 general elections marked a turning point — the Congress system of one-party dominance began to fracture:\n\n1. Electoral setbacks: Congress lost power in eight states — Rajasthan, Punjab, Haryana, UP, Bihar, West Bengal, Orissa, and Madras. For the first time, non-Congress governments took power in several major states.\n\n2. Coalition and defection politics: Non-Congress parties formed coalition governments, often unstable. 'Aaya Ram Gaya Ram' — a legislator who changed party allegiance three times in one day — became a symbol of legislative floor-crossing, leading to President's Rule in several states.\n\n3. Congress split (1969): The fundamental challenge came from within Congress itself. A battle between Indira Gandhi and the Congress 'Syndicate' (party bosses like S. Nijalingappa, K. Kamaraj) led to Congress splitting into Congress(I) (Indira) and Congress(O) (Old/Organisation).\n\n4. Rise of regional parties: Regional parties — DMK in Tamil Nadu, Akali Dal in Punjab, Left parties in Bengal — consolidated their bases, permanently ending Congress's all-India dominance." },
                { year: 2022, marks: 2, q: "What was the significance of the phrase 'Aaya Ram Gaya Ram' in Indian politics?", a: "'Aaya Ram Gaya Ram' (He came, he left) refers to a famous incident in 1967 when a Haryana legislator named Gaya Lal changed his party affiliation three times in a single day. The phrase became a metaphor for the rampant floor-crossing and defection culture that destabilised Indian state governments in the late 1960s-70s.\n\nSignificance: It highlighted a serious flaw in parliamentary democracy — elected representatives switching parties for personal gain, causing instability. It eventually led to the passage of the Anti-Defection Law (10th Schedule, 1985) which disqualifies legislators who switch parties or defy party whip." }
