                { year: 2024, marks: 4, q: "What was the Chipko Movement? What were its demands and significance?", a: "The Chipko Movement was a grassroots environmental movement that began in the Uttarakhand Himalayas in 1973. The name comes from the Hindi word 'chipko' (to hug) — villagers hugged trees to prevent loggers from felling them.\n\nOrigin: Loggers contracted by the government came to cut trees in Gopeshwar (Chamoli district). Local women, led by activists associated with Chandi Prasad Bhatt and Sunderlal Bahuguna, embraced the trees to prevent felling.\n\nDemands:\n1. Stop commercial logging in the Himalayas\n2. Protect the ecological stability of the mountains — forests prevent landslides, maintain watersheds, and sustain village livelihoods\n3. Local communities must have rights over local forest resources\n\nSignificance:\n1. Environmental victory: The movement led to a 15-year moratorium on commercial felling in the Uttarakhand Himalayas — a major environmental policy win.\n2. Women's empowerment: It was a women-led movement, placing women at the centre of environmental activism. It showed the link between women's livelihoods and forest protection.\n3. Ecological consciousness: Chipko inspired environmental movements worldwide and raised awareness about the link between forests, water, and mountain communities.\n4. Democracy lesson: Non-violent direct action by ordinary citizens achieved what formal politics had not." },
                { year: 2023, marks: 3, q: "What were the Dalit Panthers? What were their main demands?", a: "The Dalit Panthers was a militant Dalit rights organisation founded in 1972 in Maharashtra, inspired by the Black Panther movement in the USA.\n\nFounding context: Despite the constitutional abolition of untouchability, Dalits in Maharashtra (and across India) continued to face violent atrocities, social discrimination, and economic exploitation. Young Dalit intellectuals and activists felt the need for more confrontational action.\n\nMain demands:\n1. Strict enforcement of laws against caste discrimination and untouchability\n2. Land redistribution to landless Dalit agricultural labourers\n3. End to bonded labour and agricultural exploitation\n4. Economic and social equality — implementation of reservations and affirmative action\n5. Cultural assertion of Dalit identity and pride, drawing on the legacy of Dr B.R. Ambedkar\n\nSignificance: The Dalit Panthers represented a shift from social reform to political confrontation — Dalits asserting their rights rather than appealing for sympathy. Their influence shaped the emergence of Dalit politics in Maharashtra and inspired similar movements across India." }
