                { year: 2024, marks: 4, q: "Describe the main features of the Punjab crisis. How was it resolved?", a: "The Punjab Crisis of the 1980s was the most serious internal security challenge India faced in that decade:\n\nBackground:\n- Sikh demands for greater autonomy had been building since the 1970s. The Anandpur Sahib Resolution (1973) demanded more autonomy for Punjab and a Chandigarh transfer.\n- Militant groups, supported by Pakistan, turned the movement violent. Armed militants under Jarnail Singh Bhindranwale operated from the Golden Temple in Amritsar.\n\nKey events:\n1. Operation Bluestar (June 1984): Prime Minister Indira Gandhi ordered the Indian Army to enter the Golden Temple to flush out armed militants. The operation killed Bhindranwale and hundreds of militants but caused widespread outrage among Sikhs worldwide for violating the sanctity of their holiest shrine.\n2. Assassination of Indira Gandhi: Two months later, Indira Gandhi was assassinated by her Sikh bodyguards. This was followed by anti-Sikh riots in Delhi and other cities, killing thousands.\n3. Operation Black Thunder (1988): Further military action cleared militants from the Golden Temple.\n\nResolution: The Rajiv-Longowal Accord (Punjab Accord, 1985) with Akali Dal leader Harchand Singh Longowal accepted many Sikh demands. Although Longowal was assassinated, elections in Punjab eventually restored normal democratic politics by the early 1990s." },
                { year: 2023, marks: 3, q: "What is the Assam Accord? What were its main provisions?", a: "The Assam Accord (1985) was a tripartite agreement signed between the Government of India, the Government of Assam, and the All Assam Students' Union (AASU) and All Assam Gana Sangram Parishad (AAGSP), bringing an end to the six-year Assam Agitation.\n\nBackground: The Assam movement (1979-85) protested against illegal immigration from Bangladesh, claiming it was altering Assam's demographic and cultural character.\n\nMain provisions:\n1. Foreigners detected: All persons who entered Assam illegally between January 1, 1966 and March 24, 1971 would be detected, deleted from electoral rolls, but could stay and apply for citizenship after 10 years.\n2. Post-1971 deportation: Foreigners who entered Assam after March 25, 1971 would be detected and deported.\n3. Constitutional safeguards: The accord promised legislative and economic measures to protect the cultural, social, and linguistic identity of the Assamese people.\n4. Development: Special development projects for Assam.\n\nLimitations: Implementation has been slow and contested — the National Register of Citizens (NRC) exercise is linked to the unresolved issues the Assam Accord left behind." }
