                { year: 2024, marks: 3, q: "What is the central theme of 'My Mother at Sixty-Six'? Explain the contrasting imagery used.", a: "The central theme of Kamala Das's poem is the fear of losing one's mother — the helplessness of watching a beloved parent age and the inevitability of death and separation.\n\nContrasting imagery:\n1. The mother's face: The poet looks at her mother dozing in the car and sees 'her face ashen like that of a corpse' — pale, still, lifeless. This simile captures the poet's fear that her mother, once the centre of warmth and life, is fading.\n\n2. The trees and children: To escape this frightening image, the poet looks out the car window and sees 'young trees sprinting' and 'merry children spilling out of their homes' — images of vitality, speed, and joy — the polar opposite of her mother's stillness.\n\n3. The parting: At the airport, the poet smiles and waves, but the smile conceals her aching fear. She hopes to 'see her again' — a phrase weighted with uncertainty. The poem ends without resolution, holding the fear suspended.\n\nThe contrast between the mother's stillness and the world's vitality outside captures the universal grief of watching a parent approach death, while the world moves on indifferently." },
                { year: 2023, marks: 2, q: "What does the poet mean by 'that pain' in the poem 'My Mother at Sixty-Six'?", a: "'That pain' refers to a familiar, childhood fear that resurfaces in the adult poet — the old, deep-seated terror of losing her mother. The poet had felt this fear as a child (perhaps dreading separation) and now it returns with greater force as she sees her ageing mother's pale face. 'That familiar ache' and 'that old familiar pain' are the same primal emotion: the fear of her mother's death and the unbearable thought of life without her." }
