                { year: 2024, marks: 3, q: "What is the central message of 'A Thing of Beauty'? What things does Keats describe as sources of beauty?", a: "The central message of John Keats's poem (from Endymion) is that a thing of beauty is a permanent source of joy — 'a joy forever.' Beauty does not fade or diminish with time; its loveliness increases. More importantly, beautiful things are not mere pleasures — they are sources of psychic shelter and healing. They 'remove the pall from our dark spirits.'\n\nSources of beauty Keats describes:\n1. The sun, moon, and old and young trees — providing shade and shelter\n2. Simple sheep — and their shelter in clover\n3. Daffodils with green cover\n4. Clear rills (streams) that run in forests\n5. The midforest brake (dense forest) — a cool, leafy retreat\n6. The grandeur of noble natures — stories of the mighty dead — such as great heroes\n7. All lovely tales that we have heard or read (myths, legends)\n\nKeats argues that these beautiful things are 'an endless fountain of immortal drink' — they nourish the soul. In a world full of 'despondence,' 'gloomy days,' and human suffering, beauty is the one constant that sustains the spirit." }
