                { year: 2023, marks: 3, q: "What is the central theme of 'A Roadside Stand'? What does Frost say about those who claim to help the rural poor?", a: "Robert Frost's poem depicts a small, rough roadside stand set up by poor rural farmers beside the highway, hoping that passing city cars will stop and buy their produce — giving them a share of the city's wealth.\n\nCentral theme: The vast economic and social divide between city dwellers and rural poor. The farmers' hope for some of the city's money — enough to partake in modern life ('money, the cash, whose flow supports / The flower of cities from sinking and withering faint') — goes largely unfulfilled. City cars speed past, or stop to complain about the poor positioning of the stand.\n\nOn those who claim to help: Frost bitterly describes 'greedy good-doers' and 'beneficent beasts of prey' — well-meaning urban do-gooders and government planners who want to move the rural poor to 'villages of initiative.' The irony: these helpers act not from genuine understanding of what the poor want (inclusion in prosperity, dignity) but from their own sense of what is good for the poor. The poor are displaced from their land and herded into managed communities — losing their independence without gaining real prosperity.\n\nFrost ends with a complex emotion: he wishes he could put the pain of these desperate farmers to sleep — but he cannot. Their suffering is real and unresolved." }
