                { year: 2024, marks: 4, q: "What does the third level in Jack Finney's story symbolise? Do you think it is real or just a waking-dream fantasy?", a: "In Jack Finney's story, the narrator Charley claims to have found a 'third level' at Grand Central Station in New York — a level that doesn't officially exist, transporting him to 1894.\n\nSymbolism: The third level symbolises escapism — the human desire to flee from the stresses of modern life into an idealised past. The story is set in the early 1950s, when the world was grappling with Cold War anxiety. Charley's psychiatrist friend Sam interprets the third level as a 'waking-dream wish fulfilment' — Charley's mind creating an escape from the tensions of modern existence. The idyllic Galesburg of 1894 represents a simpler, gentler world — slow trains, slow news, front porches, and peace.\n\nReal or imaginary? The story leaves this deliberately ambiguous. Charley's wife Louisa finds an 1894 letter from Sam — suggesting Sam actually escaped to the third level. But it could also be an elaborate wish-fulfilment that Charley has woven. The story's power lies in not resolving this — instead, it asks: Does it matter? The yearning for escape is real, even if the third level is not.\n\nKey message: Modern life creates anxiety that makes people yearn for imagined refuges — but the past is an illusion, and escapism is not a solution." }
